node.text:
"We always knew we once had a whole bunch of Indians living around here, because we had found way too many artifacts to think otherwise. But we had no idea... how big it was."⁠
⁠
People in rural areas of south-central Kansas had been turning up scattered Native American artifacts that were more than four centuries old for years, but didn't know their source. Then, in 2017, a high school student stumbled upon a cannonball that finally allowed researchers to confirm that the area was once home to the second-largest Native American city in history.⁠
⁠
Step inside the lost world of Etzanoa by clicking the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.text:
As one of Al Capone's right-hand men in Prohibition-era Chicago, Tony Accardo regularly murdered enemies of the Outfit on his bosses' orders. Widely believed to be one of the gunmen behind 1929's notorious St. Valentine's Day Massacre, Accardo is just as notorious for an incident in which he dispatched several of Capone's enemies with his weapon of choice: a baseball bat. After the grisly deed was done, Capone supposedly said, "Boy, this kid's a real Joe Batters" — and the nickname stuck for the rest of Accardo's blood-soaked career.⁠
⁠
Follow the link in our profile to discover the outrageous stories behind some of the most colorful nicknames in mob history.⁠
⁠
⁠
⁠

node.text:
Before there was Cindy or Naomi, there was Gia Carangi, the "it girl" of the late 70s and 80s who brought edge and electricity to New York's fashion scene. Carangi was posed to be the supermodel who defined the era, but she suffered an untimely death after battling an addiction to drugs and complications from an AIDS diagnosis. During her sweeping decline, Crawford booked many jobs that had been planned for Carangi, promptly rising her to stardom.⁠
⁠
Learn more about the short-lived career of supermodel Gia Carangi by following the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.text:
In 1850, Queen Victoria met a 7-year-old orphan named Sarah Forbes Bonetta. Although the young West African child had just been brought out of slavery, the Queen soon learned that Bonetta was actually a royal.⁠
⁠
Born a princess of the Yoruba people, Bonetta had been enslaved after a rival tribe killed her family. In a twist of fate, she had crossed paths with a sympathetic British sea captain who brought her back to England with him. Despite the child's traumatic early life, Victoria declared the girl "sharp and intelligent" — and decided to become her godmother.⁠
⁠
But Bonetta's life would be far from perfect — read more at the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Scotland. May be an image of outdoors and text that says 'For $173, $173,000 This Eerie Abandoned Village In Scotland Could Be All Yours'.

node.text:
The Old Village of Lawers in the Scottish Highlands is currently on sale for $173,000. But the purchase comes with a catch — potentially being haunted by the 450-year-old ghost of the Lady of Lawers, a famed soothsayer and prophet who foresaw death and destruction.⁠
⁠
She predicted the land clearances of the 19th century which left the village all but abandoned by 1841 when only 17 of its 3,500 residents remained. The Lady of Lawers predicted, “The land will first be sifted, then riddled of its people. The jaw of the sheep will drive the plough from the ground.” And indeed, the Scottish clearances express purpose was to create more grazing ground for sheep. Learn more about this Scottish village up for sale by clicking the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠

According to Shakespeare's play "The King," it's only after Henry's father died that he transformed into a commanding leader — but historians will be quick to remind us that this was not based in fact. In reality, Prince Henry played an important role in his father's regime, and it was his political involvement — not his supposed political indifference — that often led to disagreements between father and son.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read the true story of Henry V.⁠
⁠

node.text:
Few know that Native American tribes took advantage of the transatlantic slave trade too — and could be every bit as merciless as their white counterparts. "They were willful and determined oppressors of blacks they owned, enthusiastic participants in a global economy driven by cotton, and believers in the idea that they were equal to whites and superior to blacks."⁠
⁠
Then in 1842, over two dozen African slaves in Oklahoma tried to escape to Mexico — only to be hunted down by 100 Choctaw and Cherokee warriors who would capture and execute five of them.⁠
⁠
Go inside the bitter slave revolt that most American history books leave out by clicking the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠
⁠
#historyofoklahoma #cherokees #oklahoma #slaverevolts #ushistory #historyuncovered #josephvann

Undeterred, she tried to register to vote in 1965 and while standing line, was accosted by a notoriously racist police officer. After he tried to force her out with his nightstick, she punched him twice in the mouth- and nearly was charged with attempted murder.'.

node.text:
Meet Annie Lee Cooper, the activist who civil rights leader John Lewis once described as “Upfront, pleasant and… absolutely fearless.” ⁠
⁠
In 1965, Cooper was arrested from a Selma, Alabama courthouse while attempting to register to vote. When a cop tried to remove her from the line, Cooper socked him twice in the jaw. Though she was consequently beaten, arrested, and nearly charged with attempted murder, Cooper continued to fight for racial justice and even joined MLK on his freedom march between Selma and Montgomery that March. This is her fearless tale — read more at the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠
#annieleecooper #blackhistory #activists #selma #alabama #jimcrow #ushistory

node.text:
In 1921, Roscoe "Fatty" Arbuckle was the highest-paid actor in the world — but after the mysterious death of aspiring actress Virginia Rappe, he never appeared on screen again.⁠
⁠
Both were attendees of a party at the St. Francis Hotel in San Francisco and were briefly in the same hotel room together. But when Arbuckle left the room, Rappe remained on a bed "writhing in pain." Four days later, she was dead of a ruptured bladder.⁠
⁠
After a sensationalized media scandal, trial for manslaughter, and subsequent acquittal, Arbuckle was a free man — and an out-of-work star. Click the link in our profile to learn more about the mystery that still looms over this tragic Hollywood death. ⁠
⁠
⁠

"It is just the most exquisite thing and to have found it literally in a pile of rubble is probably… well, it’s unheard of."⁠
⁠
Workers in the middle of renovating the attic of a British nobleman's Tudor mansion just found a trove of 2,000 artifacts, some of which date back to the 1400s. Follow the link in our profile to see more of the treasures they found languishing under an inch-thick layer of dust beneath the floorboards.⁠

node.text:
In 1944, a U.S. military pilot-in-training named Hazel Ying Lee crash-landed in a Kansas wheat field — where she found herself most unwelcome. The farmer who owned the field apparently thought that Lee was a Japanese invader, and he soon began chasing her around with his pitchfork, shouting to his neighbors that the Japanese were coming for Kansas. Before long, Lee found herself surrounded by the farmer's angry neighbors. Never one to lose her cool, she simply told them over and over again that she was an American fighter pilot until they finally backed off.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our profile to read the extraordinary true story of how Hazel Lee became the first Chinese American woman to fly for the U.S. military.⁠
⁠
⁠
#hazellee #asianamericanhistory #worldwar2 #ushistory #militaryhistory

node.text:
"May he rot in hell."⁠
⁠
The June 2020 trial of the Golden State Killer in Sacramento, California was filled with emotion. Joseph James DeAngelo plead guilty to 13 counts of first-degree murder and admitted to having 87 victims across 57 incidents during the 1970s and 80s.⁠
⁠
He received 11 consecutive life sentences — but not before hearing from the families of his victims. One woman recalled being 7-years-old and asleep as the Golden State Killer bound and raped her mother in a neighboring bedroom. "He threatened to cut my ear off and bring it to her," she told the court and said that DeAngelo was "proof monsters were real. I had met the boogeyman."⁠
⁠
Read more about how the Golden State Killer finally met justice by clicking the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
⁠
